Data Collection



Getting the data was by far the simplest part of the process. I obtained the station values, the station metadata, and combined them together.



I queried data provided by NRCS, using their query tool.



In order to have the most frequent weather observations possible, but at the same time query a workable amount of data, I decided to pull semi-monthly values. I tried to first pull daily values, but it said the query was too big for going back to 1978, which was as far back as I could go for most of the data. 1



Here is a snapshot of the data:





You can see that the columns needed formatting, for example to create a date column, or to eliminate unuseful columns, like change_snow_water.

I obtained the station metadata through the snotelr R package.



The metadata.





I then combined the metadata with the actual values. And with the joined data, cleaned up the columns.





As you can see, there were some obvious problems with the data. There were NA values, as well as maximum (max_temp_mean) and minumum (min_temp_mean) temperatures that werent possible - 407, 389.. This warranted some data exploration and statistical intervention.
